data.content:
In xUnit, setup/teardown is handled through constructors, `IDisposable`, and `IClassFixture<T>`:

```csharp
// Shared class-level setup/teardown via a fixture
public class DatabaseFixture : IAsyncLifetime
{
    public Task InitializeAsync()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    }

    public Task DisposeAsync()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
        return Task.CompletedTask;
    }
}

// Test class uses constructor/Dispose for per-test setup/teardown
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // [SetUp] → constructor
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // [TearDown] → IDisposable.Dispose
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

**Key mappings:**

| NUnit | xUnit |
|-------|-------|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + fixture constructor/`InitializeAsync` |
| `[OneTimeTearDown]` | Fixture's `Dispose`/`DisposeAsync` |

The fixture is instantiated once and shared across all tests in the class.
